    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-02-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-02-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="539"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d539">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 882.00/527</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of the Navy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 14, 1916</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your letter of the 9th of February, informing the Department of the proposed
                    withdrawal of the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Chester</hi> from Liberian waters,
                    and in reply <pb facs="0531" n="455" xml:id="pg_455"/> to say that a telegram
                    has been received from the American Minister at Monrovia recommending, with the
                    concurrence of the commander of the vessel, that its station at Monrovia be
                    continued at least two weeks after the arrival of the arms and ammunition which
                    the Government of Liberia has recently purchased in this country.</p>
                <p>Great good has been accomplished by the presence of the U. S. S. <hi
                        rend="italic">Chester</hi> in West African waters in preventing a more
                    extended uprising of native tribes which so seriously threatened the Republic,
                    and I take this occasion to express the Department’s deep appreciation of the
                    valuable assistance rendered by your Department in causing the vessel to be put
                    to that useful service.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
